<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUNG ADULTS' INABILITY TO BUY OWN HOME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kudos to Robert Kuttner ("The Great Generational Depression," Commentary, Sept. 
3) and the few other souls in the (economic) wilderness for pointing out a 
recent American phenomenon: the hard fact that a young family, by itself, will 
never be able to own their own home. 
</P>
<P>
Kuttner cites some (all too familiar to me) data, but what impressed me the 
most was his theory: that the reason why "the political system is paying so 
little attention to this remarkable generational economic distress . . . is 
because the distress has yet to reach the opinion-leader class in a serious 
way." 
</P>
<P>
The fact today is that if you're young, and don't have a great deal of personal 
wealth, or at least parents of means, then the only way you're gonna own a home 
is to be a highly paid professional -- at least $65,000 a year. Then marry a 
similar young professional and combine your incomes toward the purchase of your 
home. You may be able to afford a small place in a not-too-objectionable part 
of town. And whatever you do, don't make the mistake of having children! This 
will put one-half of the mortgage-paying team out of commission for several 
critical months! I mean, what do you want, a family or a home? 
</P>
<P>
You tell the older generation this, and they'll never believe you. If you ask 
the government for help, you are sent a list of no-money-down fixer-uppers. My 
parents nod in sympathy, but, you see, they're financially strapped because of 
that condo in Maui. 
</P>
<P>
TODD WAITE 
</P>
<P>
Van Nuys 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
