<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOR MOST OF US, THE NO. 1 ISSUE IS NO BIG DEAL; 
</P>
<P>
CRIME: IT'S DOWN IN CALIFORNIA, BUT THE POLITICIANS STILL FIND IT AN EASY 
ATTENTION-GETTER. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN WALTERS, Dan Walters is a political columnist for the Sacramento Bee. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A monumental paradox has surfaced in this election season: While polls and 
other measures of public sentiment indicate ever-rising levels of concern about 
crime -- and coincidental levels of support for more laws and more cops and 
prisons -- Californians' actual chances of being victims of crime have been 
declining rather markedly. 
</P>
<P>
A month ago, the Department of Justice issued, with little official fanfare and 
equally scant media interest, a thick report on crime in California during the 
1980s. During the decade, the California Crime Index -- the number of serious 
crimes per 100,000 population -- decreased sharply from nearly 4,000 in 1980 to 
less than 3,500 in 1989, even counting an upward bump in the last two years of 
the period. 
</P>
<P>
While the actual number of crimes may have increased, that has been offset by 
the state's huge population growth during the period, roughly 6 million. In 
other words, crime grew more slowly than population; or, to say it still 
another way, one's statistical chances of becoming a crime victim decreased. 
</P>
<P>
During that same period, moreover, the "clearance rate" for crimes increased by 
14%, although only about 22% of all major crimes were being cleared by arrest 
or other actions. And, as everyone knows, the number of criminals being locked 
up has escalated sharply. 
</P>
<P>
If relatively fewer crimes are being committed, more are being solved and more 
felons are going to jail, that should be cause for great celebration. We should 
be congratulating ourselves that all of those additional laws and billions of 
tax dollars are having a major impact. 
</P>
<P>
Why, then, are Californians more, not less, concerned about crime? 
</P>
<P>
For one thing, the decrease in crime is a big secret, one that the crime 
industry wants to keep locked away. Think of the hundreds of thousands of cops, 
lawyers, judges, prison guards, prison builders, gun and lock merchants, 
insurance agents, burglar alarm installers and others whose incomes depend on 
crime. Even the military wants to get in on the crime-fighting trade these days 
as its main reason for being, the Soviet Union, becomes a pussycat. 
</P>
<P>
Chief among those who engage in the conspiracy of silence about crime are 
politicians. Contemporary political campaigns consist of identifying supposed 
threats to the welfare of voters and then promising to oppose them effectively. 
</P>
<P>
Bombarded by real and fictional crimes daily through the media, we become more 
acutely sensitive to incidents from our own lives and thus become utterly 
convinced that waves of crime are threatening to inundate us. 
</P>
<P>
Crime is, in fact, a very serious matter in some inner-city neighborhoods. But 
for most Californians, it is a minor annoyance at most, certainly not something 
that should preoccupy their lives. 
</P>
<P>
The danger is that politicians will continue to dwell on crime for tactical 
reasons, not only contributing to the irrational climate of fear, but also 
neglecting policy issues that are fundamentally more important to the state's 
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091290-0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 274792 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 12, 1990, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 8; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
593 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
3,000-ACRE BLAZE NEAR ESCONDIDO ALMOST ENCIRCLED; EVACUEES RETURNING; 
</P>
<P>
BRUSH FIRE: TWO HUNDRED WERE FORCED TO FLEE CANYON RESIDENCES. FIVE HOMES WERE 
BADLY DAMAGED. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RAY TESSLER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 3,000-acre brush fire west of Escondido, believed to have been caused by 
illegal target shooting, was nearly encircled by 600 firefighters late Tuesday, 
as evacuated residents went back to their blackened canyon of posh houses. 
</P>
<P>
Capt. A.D. Hill of the California Department of Forestry predicted that the 
blaze, which forced about 200 residents to flee and seriously damaged five 
homes, would be extinguished by 8 p.m. today. 
</P>
<P>
Firefighters still battled hot spots Tuesday, one of which started when a rat 
caught fire and ran east of Del Dios Highway, torching brush perilously close 
to the hamlet of Del Dios. 
</P>
<P>
With each outbreak, helicopters quickly swooped down on nearby Lake Hodges, 
filling huge buckets with water and conducting air strikes on the burning 
brush. 
</P>
<P>
"Any one of those hot spots, the wind can kick up and blow it down on the 
lake," said Ken Rice, a battalion chief with the San Diego Fire Department. 
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, fire crews were trying to contain as much of the remaining blaze as 
possible, while worrying that a shift in the wind could carry the flames 
northwest into the Harmony Grove area of Escondido. 
</P>
<P>
With low humidity and the temperature 95 degrees in the shade, conditions were 
"less than ideal" for battling a fire, Hills said. 
</P>
<P>
"We're going to hit it as hard as we can as early as we can," he said. 
</P>
<P>
As the fire began rapidly moving along Mt. Israel Road on Monday afternoon, 
fire officials ordered people to leave their canyon homes. 
</P>
<P>
About 100 of them took refuge for the night with friends or relatives and 100 
others stayed in a Red Cross shelter set up at Del Dios Middle School. 
</P>
<P>
Jerry Somohano of the Red Cross said that while many refugees returned to their 
homes Tuesday afternoon, they were expected back in the shelter Tuesday night 
because water, telephone and electrical service had not yet been restored in 
the canyon. 
</P>
<P>
The people who ventured back to their homes were sad but generally grateful the 
damage was not worse. 
</P>
<P>
Ray Saatjian, his hair matted with sweat, busily inspected his rose-growing 
operation, bemoaning the loss of about 15,000 bushes, a third of his plants. 
Seven of his eight greenhouses were damaged, along with his office. He 
estimated the damage at about $90,000. 
</P>
<P>
But Saatjian's main concern was fixing the water pipes around his property in 
hopes of saving the rest of his roses. 
</P>
<P>
"The roses are very dry, whatever is left of them," he said. "They need water 
but the line is burned around the perimeter." 
</P>
<P>
Because insurance is so expensive, "you're pretty much on your own," he said, 
so he simply plans to begin again. 
</P>
<P>
"We have no choice; we have to pull together and rebuild," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Another canyon resident, John Love, returned to find that fire had burned all 
the way around his house, but stayed about 10 feet away from the structure. 
</P>
<P>
Then he learned that Jim Bell, a 29-year-old bulldozer operator who was working 
on a recreational project when he saw the fire approach, had swung into action 
and cut a fire break around Love's home. 
</P>
<P>
"He went up there like John Wayne," said Love. "He saved my home." 
</P>
<P>
Bell, who stayed up all night and most of Tuesday helping, said, "I was just 
trying to save people's houses. I've worked up here and these are good folks. I 
wasn't trying to be a hero, that's for sure." 
</P>
<P>
Fire officials have no total damage estimate and no suspects in the fire, which 
Hill blamed on target shooting nearby. 
</P>
<P>
"I understand it was a high-powered weapon of some type," he said. He 
speculated that the spark from the muzzle may have ignited the blaze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BRUSH FIRES -- SAN DIEGO COUNTY; EVACUATIONS; PROPERTY DAMAGE 
