<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
CINEPLEX BOX OFFICE DISAPPOINTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TORONTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Summer box office receipts for Cineplex Odeon Corp., one of North America's 
biggest movie theater chains, are not as strong as the money-losing company 
hoped, President and Chief Executive Officer Allen Karp said today. 
</P>
<P>
But he still expects Cineplex's earnings for the peak movie-going summer season 
to be higher than in 1989, in contrast to the rest of the industry, which he 
believes will earn less. 
</P>
<P>
"It was a tough summer," Karp said in an interview. "But we had a couple of 
advantages going for us." He mentioned Cineplex's performance in Canada and its 
conservative bidding that helped it avoid some highly touted films that did 
poorly. 
</P>
<P>
Cineplex, which loaded itself with debt because of over-ambitious expansion 
plans, lost $50.4 million in the first half of 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
