<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
JAPAN TRADE SURPLUS WIDENS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus with the rest of the world widened 3.7% in August while 
its surplus with the United States narrowed, the Finance Ministry said today. 
</P>
<P>
The overall surplus grew to an unadjusted $3.49 billion in August from $3.37 
billion in August, 1989, the ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
It was the third time this year that the nation's trade gap has widened 
compared with a year earlier. The surplus had declined for 11 consecutive 
months until March. 
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus with the United States narrowed to $2.83 billion from 
$3.01 billion in August last year. 
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the United States shrank because of lower demand for Japanese 
exports resulting from a slowing U.S. economy, economists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
