<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
PBA CLEARED IN BOWLING BALL SUIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ST. LOUIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal court has dismissed a multimillion-dollar antitrust lawsuit filed by 
a bowling ball manufacturer against the Professional Bowlers Assn. 
</P>
<P>
The suit was filed in 1988 by EurekaUrethane Inc. of St. Louis after the PBA 
did not clear for use in its tournaments a bowling ball the firm produced that 
carried a beer company's product name and logo. 
</P>
<P>
In his ruling last week, Judge Stephen N. Limbaugh said the PBA's actions in 
refusing to sanction the ball were "neither unreasonable nor anti-competitive" 
and were "a sound exercise of business judgment calculated to preserve their 
ability to serve the interests of professional bowlers." 
</P>
